                type="document" xml:id="d58">
                <head>58. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>During a TASS broadcast at 7 p.m. EDT on August 30, 1961, the Soviet Union
                    announced that it was resuming atomic testing. For text, see <hi rend="italic"
                        >Documents on Disarmament, 1961</hi>, pages 347-348. Through intelligence
                    channels, the U.S. Government had prior knowledge of the announcement and began
                    drafting a statement that was released by the White House at approximately 9
                    p.m. (Memoranda of telephone conversations: <persName corresp="#p_RD3"
                        >Rusk</persName>-<persName corresp="#p_SAEII1">Stevenson</persName>,
                        <persName corresp="#p_RD3">Rusk</persName>-<persName corresp="#p_BCE2"
                        >Bohlen</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_RD3">Rusk</persName>-<persName
                        corresp="#p_BMG2">Bundy</persName>, and <persName corresp="#p_RD3"
                        >Rusk</persName>-<persName corresp="#p_WJB1">Wiesner</persName>, all the
                    evening of August 30; Department of State, <persName corresp="#p_RD3"
                        >Rusk</persName> Files: Lot 72 D 192, Telephone Conversations) For text of
                    the announcement, <hi rend="italic">see Documents on Disarmament, 1961</hi>,
                    pages 348-350. The memorandum of <persName corresp="#p_RD3">Rusk</persName>’s
                    telephone conversation with <persName corresp="#p_WJB1">Wiesner</persName>
                    indicates that <persName corresp="#p_DAH1">Dean</persName>’s recall, announced
                    in the statement, was initiated by the President.</p>
            </div>
